column14: My company will specialize in buying top selling video game licenses and dub the score/script into the Arabic language. Furthermore, a website with an online store will be created in order to host my products and a complete online marketing strategy will ensure visibility and increase sales. In the future the company will develop Arabic video games in house and contribute in creating local job opportunities.
column15:
My target audience will be local and regional Arabs from different age group that have access to the internet and would be interested in my products. 49% of the online users in MENA region are under twenty five years of age.
33% of the online users in the MENA region are between 26 and 35 years of age.
The rest of the online users (18%) in the MENA region are over 35 years of age.
It is important to note that the purchasing power is divided between these three groups. We will have a variety in our products that would appeal to large chunk of MENA online users.
column16: Since the nature of our product will appeal to Arabs, the major geographical target market would be the MENA region. Nevertheless, expatriates all over the globe could purchase our products through an easy 3 step online checkout system. In the beginning it is important to target the GCC countries because they have the largest percentage of purchasing power between all the regional countries.
column17: according to the internet world stats and the MADAR research, 34 million internet users in the Middle East, 17.5 million users in the GCC-Levant region, with 920% growth from year 2000 to 2007. the size of the market would be at a minimum of 34 million dollars.
column18: My competitors in the Middle East would be established video game resellers, video game developers and international distributors. Already a social network base online video game called trivian.ae is being marketed extensively all over the net and is ranking extremely high in terms of visibility and online user registration. As long as the internet penetration is growing in the MENA region, I would expect a equal growth of competitors in the next 5 years.
column19: My product would consist of popular video games that are being dubbed into an Arabic and this alone is a new concept that would be Attractive to my target audience. Furthermore, in order to appeal to a larger audience, i will get popular Arab sports anchors and celebrities to dub the scripts and characters. My products would bring a customized video gaming experience that is totally adapted to an Arab audience. My products would be supported by online forums where people can join and connect, all in Arabic. My products will be high in quality at affordable prices. My products would be accessible to all age groups and purchased at all major retail stores and/or online.
column24: As long as i am the first to acquire the licenses of top selling and popular video games and guarantee a distribution exclusivity, I would be ahead of any competition at least for the first 36 months. Soon enough, the company will start by developing video games in house both for consoles and the internet and take the advantage over any competitor that tries to catch on.
column25: I would estimate that the company would break even after 24 months. The budget for the first year would be mainly spent on acquiring the video game licenses, setting up the studio, developing the website and finalizing the product. The second year"s budget would be spent mainly on marketing, distribution creating a sales force and continuing to acquire licenses.
column26: I would estimate that the first sale would be made 8-10 months after i start.
column27: The lack of experience is the major risk that is running against me. I plan to be surrounded by experienced advisers and consult some risk management firms. column14: Our Company will design, print and distribute the Cairo t-shirt (similar to the I LOVE NY shirt). This t-shirt will be positioned as a social movement and will capture the feelings of our generation towards a city we love to hate. Several t-shirts will be created focusing on aspects of the city we truly hate (pollution, traffic, garbage etc.). Each t-shirt will focus on a different problem and turn it into something we love, i.e. I Love (Heart) Cairo Traffic.  In addition to the t-shirt, key-chains, bumper stickers, towels etc. will be designed. As the Company grows more designs and ideas will be printed on the shirts. Finally, a percentage of the profits will go towards helping our city and its people which will also serve as marketing for our product.

column16: In addition to Cairo, we will sell and distribute these t-shirts and merchandise directly in other countries. Expats abroad have already shown interest in the product and have a willingness to distribute in those countries: Canada, US, and England.
column18: Currently, there are no competitors in the market that offer even a remotely similar product. Yet it will be easy for copycats of our t-shirts. column14: Our company will provide a website which connects people who want to learn a topic(such a language, or resume writing), with educators in the global community who have knowledge on the topic. This community based learning approach allows anyone to play the role of both educator and learner. We will provide the technology to connect learners and educators and facilitate remote learning.
column15: Our target clients will be primarily high school and university aged people(16-30)  who are computer literate, own a PC, and have access to an internet connection.We expect to appeal mainly to people who are typically familiar with social networking sites such as Facebook and Twitter.
column16: Our target market will be major urban areas with high schools and universities. We will target mainly gulf countries where the level of internet usage is the highest, especially amongst high-school and university aged students, and where the average disposable income amongst this age group is the highest.
column17: We estimate the advertisement market on websites to be around $5,000,000 in 2009 from direct advertisements or through 3rd parties. As for the market of typical elearning websites it"s less than that, around $100,000.
column18: Our service is unique and isn"t offered anywhere in the world because we adopt a social networking approach to learning and allow users to connect with any educators in the global community to learn about any topic of their interest.  That being said,  we will still compete indirectly with online learning schools such as onlinelearning.net which typically offer certificate programs for individuals wishing to learn a particular trade for future work. Additionally we we will be competing with local schools and universities which offer tutoring, extracurricular programs, and workshops.
column19: We offer our clients the ability to choose educators based on a variety of factors such as geographical proximity, client ratings and reviews, language of instruction, time of course offerings, and methods of instruction (audio, video, in person). Unlike our competitors, this effectively allows our clients to tailor a course to their personal needs. Additionally since we are a social networking site, we will scale better. This means as the user base grows, so do the number of educators, and the variety and number of courses offered. Additionally, a growing user base also allows for healthy competition between educators competing for students, and this effectively should drive our prices lower than our competitors over the long run.

column19:
The advantages that make our product suitable and competitive in its target market are:
- It provides statistical information, useful for medical research and for the development of the health industry
- It is localized (i.e. available in Arabic)
- It is affordable
- Data management becomes easier in digital format
- The application has multiple interfaces with different privileges (i.e. head of unit, doctor, secretary...)
- It has a calendar feature with the option of sending automated sms messages to both patients and doctors
- It saves office space by ridding doctors from paper documents
- It is environmentally friendly :)

In Phase 2:
- It collects "anonymized" patients data from participating physicians, and gathers them in a centralized database in order to generate more representative statistics
- The centralized database allows us to link the doctors application with the laboratories in order to improve the medical care QOS

column26:
a. Consumers: Our Company provides consumers with their choice of discount coupons absolutely free; we will even pay the postage. Thus we participate in providing their principle goods in better prices.
b. Manufacturers/Marketers: The marketer pays a fixed fee to feature a brand on our company, plus few piasters for each coupon printed and mailed. The greatest benefit for marketers is reaching their targeted consumer by spending money in the right place instead of spending big amounts of money in advertising to the whole market.
c. Retailers: There are many benefits for the retailers where a fee is paid by our company for coupons redeemed at the retailer"s stores. In addition to the discounted amounts paid to retailers against collection of the coupons. column27: Our business model is new to the Egyptian market. Introducing a free service will cause doubts that would disappear gradually as soon as the consumer receives his first coupons. The majority of Middle Eastern businesses suffer a lot in the competition vs their counterparts in Asia, Europe and the Americas in the fact that they have very weak online presence and a great deal of disconnected internal business processes. Even though each company has a company website that describes their products and services, and usually each company has their own ERP system, this is far from enough. They need to "Go Digital" across the entire business value chain starting with the consumer, all the way back to the manufacturing process. Going digital is a much talked about word nowadays, but in order to make the best out of digital, you need to bring together multidisciplinary knowledge, expertise and world class execution. column14:
@sama is an online portal for airline ticket reservation. Due to the increase of the number of carriers in the region, especially low-cost airlines, there has been an increase demand for a tool that will allow the customers to compare fairs and book the cheapest. 

@Sama is an innovative portal that will integrate with all the airlines in the region.
column16:
The global competitors such as expedia.com, kayak.com, and cheaptickets.com are only integrated with the more established carriers. However, the price sensitive users are more interested in comparing fares from the low-cost carriers. Also, most of the customers who use the standard carriers have more brand loyalty, and are not sensitive to price. 

We have identified this gap, and have surveyed 500 customers from all over the middle east, and the response was very promising. They all said that they will buy from @sama as long as we don"t add a service charge to the price.  

Here is a very interesting statistic. The volume of eCommerce transactions in the Arab World during 2009 was slightly above 1 Billion US Dollars. Quit a big number, however more than 50% of this amount is actually airline tickets. This proves that most customers like to buy their tickets online, its a great opportunity !
column29:
Our geographic target Market is the Arab World, with a special focus on the GCC. 

Our target customer persona is as follows: 
- Price sensitive
- Works in a country other than his/her own 
- Between the age of 25 and 50 years of age. 
- Might be single or married.
column32:
Our revenue model will be in the form of a flat fee commission from the airlines. Airlines are already giving travel agencies commissions, and they wouldn"t mind giving @sama the same commission. 

This revenue model is well established in the global markets and works really well. The customers end up getting great prices, and don"t have to pay more. 

Consider the following: Southwest Airlines a well established US airline has a market capitalization of $3 Billion US dollars. Cheaptickets.com a company that uses the same revenue model that @Sama will use has a market cap of $15 Billion US Dollars in the Nasdaq exchange.
column40:
The innovation that @Sama brings is related to how it will integrate with the new low-cost airlines that have been appearing lately in region specially in the GCC. 

Our tools will support XML integration with cron-job updates, in addition to manual integrations with Legacy systems.

column14: Each month, hundreds of thousands of Jordanian households receive an electricity bill under the door, which they must pay at a government office, a post office, or a bank.  In a similar light, any parking or traffic ticket a citizen receives must be paid in person at a specific government office.  In our view, this is inefficient for the citizens and costly for both the citizens and government alike.  We propose to contract with government entities such as the utility company and the traffic patrol office to set up an online service for citizens to pay their utility bills and parking tickets.  This would be a major convenience for the citizens, and it would be very cost effective for the government as the online platform would cut the costs typical in a brick and mortar operation (rent, utilities, labor, etc).
column16: We have spoken to many Jordanians who agree that it is much simpler and more effective to log on to the internet and pay a bill than it is to drive to a local office and wait in line, only to do the same.  We have studied the market in the United States where similar services exist.  Most importantly, we are in discussions with executives at the incumbent Jordan utility regarding the possibility of offering this service.
column18: Market growth is best estimated by nominal GDP growth, which is roughly 3.2%.  This number is further compounded by the dramatic increase in internet penetration (it more than doubled from 2007 to 2009 and is expected to reach 50% by the end of 2011).
column19:
Through discussion with various software developers, as well as our knowledge of programming, server maintenance, and hosting from previous work on internet businesses, we estimate the costs as follows:

Programming costs: $37,500; we reach this number by multiplying 500 hours of programming, testing, security testing, etc. by the $75 rate we would pay for top of the market programmers

Server fees: $1,000 a month for a dedicated server whereby 99.99% uptime is guaranteed.

Marketing expense: $20,000; because incentives are aligned with the government in that costs are reduced when citizens pay their bills online, the utility and traffic authority will promote the service.  This alleviates our marketing expense, but test campaigns could be beneficial.
column21: The greatest potential competitor would be the government itself if it chose to operate the online service on its own as opposed to outsource it. It would not be in the interest of the government to do so given the cost savings and efficiency of outsourcing information technology (IT) processes.
column25: The competitive advantage will be maintained only by cooperation with the government to be the incumbent supplier of this online service.  Otherwise, barriers to entry are low and other companies can offer their own software at a lower commission for citizens to pay their bills.  Only by partnering with local governments and being regarded as the dominant, incumbent supplier will success build upon success and prevent entry of competition.
column26: The competitor, or status quo of going somewhere to make a payment, is inefficient, inconvenient, and outdated.  Secure online payments will transform several bothersome errands into a few clicks.
column27: The electrical company, government, and other organizations receiving payments may eliminate the middle man (us) and offer secure online payment services directly to the customer.  By creating a single portal for all payments, however, we reduce this risk.
column29:
The target country is initially Jordan, a country in which we were born and have knowledge of local customs as well as relationships with people in various industries.  The business has ability to expand, but unbridled growth will be detrimental.  Instead, we wish to focus in Jordan first, and become the dominant (hopefully only) service supplier to the government, thus creating barriers to entry for competitors.

Our target customers are the population of Jordan that receives an electricity bill or parking ticket and has easy access to the internet. Currently, internet penetration is over 36% and rapidly rising.
column31:
For the electrical bill component:
Population of Jordan: 6 million people
Households in Jordan: ~1 million
Internet users: 1,741,000
Internet penetration: 36%
People paying bills each month: 360,000
Average bill: $60 dollars
Total yearly bill payment: 360,000 * $60 * 12 months = $259,200,000
Commission (2%): 2% of $259,200,000 = $5,184,000
column32: We will earn a commission of 2% or so from each transaction.  We are in the process of calculating the total costs for the government to offer a standard bricks and mortar operation with desk attendants to serve the population.  Because this business is only viable if the government a) chooses to allow an online platform and b) chooses to have it outsourced, the price (i.e., our commission) must be lower than its current cost to serve the community.
column40:
It is a mainstay of Jordanian life to head to a government office, a post office, or bank each month to pay the electricity bill.  It is also a fact of life that any parking or traffic violation must be resolved in person.  Our service would simplify this process as citizens would be afforded the opportunity to pay their bills or tickets online.

The convenience to the citizenry is obvious, and so is the cost effectiveness to the government.  An online portal could eliminate many jobs where government employees serve the long lines of people waiting to pay a bill.  Instead, these employees can be moved to other jobs in other areas of the economy where they can potentially have a higher productivity.  Of course the cost to the government would be a fraction of the value of each transaction.  But the savings would exceed the cost: one study in the United States valued the cost of processing an online transaction at a mere $1.60 as opposed to the $6.60 it cost for a counter transaction.  Instead of paying rent, electricity, labor, etc., the government would instead pay a fraction of each transaction.  Furthermore, in addition to reducing costs, this service has the potential to increase government revenues, as many people simply do not pay parking tickets due to the time and hassle associated with doing so.
column41: When the website is fully operational, citizens will utilize the service as soon as they learn about it.  Few people would prefer to take a drive to pay a bill rather than go online and pay it in a few easy clicks.

The size of the market is unpredictable. It would change in accordance with the population growth in the geographical marketing regions, the growth of the Islamic populations in those regions, and tourism in those regions.
It is only the share of the market which is informed about the product which could be predictable.
column29:
To begin, the market would be Dubai, and then Abu Dhabi, and later the other UAE Emirates.  After some success in those markets, the GCC region would be included. Thirdly, the other Arab countries, and finally, the Michigan, United States, Munich Germany and other areas of the western countries which have high Muslim populations who speak English, Arabic, or German.
Target customers are: firstly, young (and young at heart) Muslimas from puberty to 40 who live in the hot climates of the Muslim-dominated world and who are required to wear (or who desire to wear) modest clothing.  Secondly, we would target western, Filipino and Russian women who want to be fashionable and yet modest, because they are married to Muslims and required by their husbands to wear modest clothing.
The third target market is tourists who want to wear some "traditional clothing", and still be comfortable and attractive.
column32:

In the backup plan, the primary source of revenue would be from sales of basic items like patented Islamic head coverings, cool/washable abayas, and specially designed dickies

3. Several items of the starting line of abayas feature detachable collars and cuffs - a feature not available on the market.

column25:
Istebdaaâ€™ is based on both, the diminishing partnership model in the Islamic microfinance (a.k.a. Musharka Mutanaqessa) and the crowdfunding model. Therefore, it is based, from one hand, on  sharing profits and losses between Istedbaaâ€™s investment fund and the matched project. On another hand, it does not offer any returns on investment (ROI) except for the â€œcrowdâ€ who will get the product they crowdfunded . Of course the donors will not have any tangible ROI except the recognition of their sadaka. 

Therefore, our 3 main groups of clients (MSEs, product developers and the crowd) will only pay for results, and the fundamental upgrade in productivity and innovation due to Istebdaa" services.

Istebdaaâ€™ will invest in the â€œmatchedâ€ projects with a maximum amount of 30.000 EGP, and up to 50% of the total costs involved in the operation. In other words, after that Istebdaaâ€™ links the demand with the supply of innovation/ideas/product design it will invest in these latter as long as the total capital needed does not exceed 60.000 EGP.
The rest of the capital for each â€œmatchedâ€ projects will be shared between the firm, product designer and/or online community crowdunding (consumers or donors). The fund will go to the project itself as an independent legal entity, neither to the firm nor to the product developers solely. This will insure an additional mutual risk management, takaful. 

Every repayment of capital by the entrepreneur will diminish the total capital ratio for Istebdaaâ€™ in the project, as well as profit shares. Profits from each project are shared between stakeholders (including Istebdaaâ€™) and the firm gradually buys Istebdaaâ€™s shares in the project and share them with the designers till they both own 100% of the project within a predetermined timeline. As for the e-Sadaka and e-consumersâ€™ contributions, they will be considered as part of the MSEâ€™ shares. Any Sadaka issuer will be able to track the multiplication of his Sadaka in different projects.

The repayment period is dependent upon the pre-agreed period. It should be suitable till the development of the product (grace period till the commercialization).
An example: A Fanous Made by Egyptians
Workshops in Hussein and elsewhere, who are facing an aggressive Chinese competition through the last decade, need to innovate and upgrade the value chain for their fawanees by a cost-effective mean. Istebdaa" team will try to bring on the technical difficulties faced by those workshops and will look for solvers. 
Young innovators who might have funny and bright ideas for new forms of Fawanees. They can help workshops in adding some new functions in the products or a new production process for a better quality/price ratio. For instance, adding a new functionality to let it be useful even after the holy month ends.
As mentioned, our innovation system should be more demand-driven and based on the potential marketability and how to increase it. Therefore, Egyptian children must have a say and also contribute in the evolution of the Fanous. Throughout the portal, children and other internet-users will post ideas and suggestions for their Fanous. Through Crowdfunding, children"s parents will have the option to: (i) pay 10 LE as an e-Sadaka, (ii) pay 60 LE buy in advance the innovative fanous, and (iii) pay 120 LE and get a personalized fannous!
In addition, a contest could be organized in different regions of Egypt to let children draw the way they want their Fanous, and choosing among them the best designs.

Finally, the Fanous is the simplest example of how could we improve our economy by â€œinjectingâ€ more â€œknowledgeâ€ into it. The comeback of the Egyptian Fanous is only the beginning for a brighter future of our economy.
column40:
The Arab region is witnessing historical moments of change and hope; these youth-led movements are a clear illustration of what the synergy between youth and knowledge could do, from the one hand. Meanwhile, it has shown what societal risks can unemployment and hopelessness provoke. 
The current political change in Egypt would surely have many economic implications. The main economic challenges are, among others: (1) Fighting skilled youth unemployment , (2) Increasing the Egyptian workforce productivity  and (2) Upgrading the value-added and the marketability of the Egyptian products .
This needs an intermediation framework that matches the local societal needs, local knowledge with local and/or international markets. The main problem that is preventing any these factors from being matched was (1) the financial burden and more specifically the refusal of commercial banks to support such initiatives without any collateral, (2) the unclear perception of the innovative ideas demand & supply.

column18:
The global dental equipment and consumables market is estimated to be $27.6 billion by 2015.

The dental market size in Egypt is estimated at $50 million, in 2007.
column19:
â€¢ Size
The global dental equipment and consumables market is estimated to be $27.6 billion by 2015, growing at a CAGR of
7%. The market is expected to grow because of the tremendous demand for dental biomaterial and dental implants. It
is expected that the market for dental implants and dental biomaterials will grow at an overall CAGR of 6% and
10.5% respectively from 2010 â€“ 2015.
The dental market size in Egypt is estimated at $50 million, in 2007. Traditionally, the Egyptian market is very
sensitive to prices rather than quality or high technology, but this trend is changing towards a major attention for
reliable equipment and quality products.
column21:
*Direct Competitors: starting from 2009, there are 3 expensive devices ios3d, iTero and Lava, produced by 3 American companies but they have no agents in Egypt or in Middle East.

*Indiret Competitors: Several hundreds of dental labs that"ll produce the 3D hand-held models for the jaws and teeth manually with lack of accuracy and high cost in terms of money and effort
column25:
â€¢ Revenue Streams
Currently In Egypt, our expected customer dentist makes a 3D casted plaster frame about 2 or three times daily, and
each of these frames pay from LE 100 to 800 for each according to the plaster material and according to the part of
the jaw required to be made. And they also pays from LE 2000 to 5000 for a 3D modeling software with too much
features called â€œDolphinâ€ plus annual renewal fees from LE 500 to 1200.
The day we finish our first successful prototype, we start targeting the dental students in the Egyptian faculties with
our first by-products with special offers to build audience and try to get income cash flow so early. As we cover our
expenses and costs for, we"ll offer special invitations to access our services to special, highly-selected expected
customers then later through dental conferences start targeting medium class dentists then low class dentists with
special offers to their needs. In parallel to this, we"ll be building the supporting DICOM images viewer and 3D
modeling tool as prepaid web service on iPad and Android if needed.
column26:
Our system takes some advantages over the competitors:
1. Efficiency: error is about 2-3 micrometer over manual plaster frames because of the hand-made errors and the normalization shrinkage factor of approximately 2-3 millimeter, less production cost in terms of money and time

2. It enables our customers using our system without buying expensive devices as our direct competitors through a prepaid web service (for getting the input medical images files and processing the 3D modeling) and delivery service (for the printed models) equivalent to our system.

3. We enable our customer integrating their iProducts (iPhone, iPad) and their Android to facilitate their interfacing our system and our services by developing iOS and Android clients.
column27:
â€¢ Cost Structure
We are planning to reduce the cost as possible without sacrificing the quality as possible by depending on Hi-Tech
solutions like virtual offices, cloud computing back-end and so on. The most expensive key resources is the 3d
printers, and the most expensive key activities is the software development for the DICOM viewer and the 3D
modeler


Phase0: Construction= 1 month; Virtual office and infrastructure
Phase1: Prototyping = 3 to 4 months; first side product and the first income cash flow
Phase2: Beta = 15 to 20 months; more side-products and the occurrence of break-even point and the payback will be
near the end of this phase.
Phase3: Production = more; building the production line

We need about $15,000 to start prototyping and we can afford 15% of this cost currently
column31:
Geographically; The Egyptian market is sensitive to the price more than the quality, which is a chance to get money
early before targeting the European, American or even the gulf market which requires achieving certain quality levels
that may not be easy during the launching period

column21:
We have direct competitors such as Laboratree, Mendeley, Academia; these websites are based on the somewhat similar idea of connecting researchers. 
We consider social networks as Facebook, Google Plus and Linkedin to be indirect competitors.
column26:
Direct:What we believe will give us an advantage over these websites is:
Theyâ€™re not known in our primary targeted region, which is locally in Egypt.; the market is considered untapped.They are less comprehensive in their content while one of Sciencietyâ€™s main goals is saving time; the most important asset for researchers.
Scienciety, unlike competitors, is more about the data and less about the social network which fits, according to our preliminary research, into the paradigm of â€œScientists are not social, the data isâ€
Scienciety factors in the segment of beginners and students who have no experience in the field of research which was missed by our competitors.
Most importantly; Scienciety adds a very important part of the equation which is the funding and implementation of research. Our competitors stopped at conducting research but we believe that the purpose of research is to find solutions and actually solve, we believe that our â€œCrowd fundingâ€ tool gives us an important competetive edge.
Indirect:  Our advantage over them is the fact that Scienciety depends on the social data rather than social scientists and Scienciety provides researchers with what they specifically need in no time.
column29: Scienciety will cater to the needs of thesegment of researchers by various tools; a myriad of features to help researchers attain peer input, students to read and understand scientific journals for free, provide a coaching system, a comprehensive news feed in the latest in the customerâ€™s field of interest be it new papers, open course ware, scholarships, competitions or job vacancies, provide a platform for crowd funding and/or attracting investments and thatâ€™s just the beginning.
column31: Target audience: Students and researchers in technical fields
column32:
The field of scientific research in our country faces a lot of obstacles, be them lack of
funding, lack of resources or simply lack of support and peer input. Students and young researchers in the various technical fields in Egypt, generally, lack the know,  how and the means of conducting research, searching for resources, finding guidance for development and implementing their solutions.
column40:
A scientifically oriented social network; specifically designed to form an interlinked society of solution finders and solution implementers. Our network will cater to the needs of researchers, investors and most importantly students interested in the various fields of developing sciences, and act as bridge to connect them all together. We will mainly act on forming communication channels between all the parties involved in the scientific research process; these parties are students, researchers and investors.
The network is going to provide the users many features to help fulfilling the objective of the website. The network is going to help the students and the young researchers to get systemic coaching from other more experienced researchers. Researchers with well developed and mature ideas will be able to find crowd funding for their ideas. On the other hand, Investors will be able to find the promising ideas that they are willing to fund.
Researchers will be provided by free simplified papers, videos and all required materials to let them conduct their researches efficiently.
Our network will significantly aid all those who can help solve problems to find each other and collaborate; by doing so many researchers can overcome various obstacles that face the field of scientific research in our country, be it lack of funding, lack of resources or simply lack of support and peer input. This community will lead to a great development in the researcher, and will get the whole research world together.

column16:
Amakena uniquely uses the social aspects of the web to help users with their buying decisions.

Amakena"s simplistic design helps users work it in an intuitive way which minimizes it"s learning curve. The site adapts according to usage, categories are rearranged based on user preferences and category access frequency.

Amakena is an open platform, meaning users can add an interest category (e.g. Rare Coin collections) and invite people to join these categories. When a category gets enough activity to be considered "popular", it is enabled as one of the main categories of the site.

Amakena integrates with existing social networking sites such as Facebook, Twitter and Google allowing users to use their existing identity on Amakena.
column32:
The most important factor for retailers is "how to reach their target demographic in volume". This is the main factor that affects their choice of location, marketing , expansion, etc. While some retailers have on-line stores, most of them are failing to utilize this channel, this is mainly because most retailers fail to realize that these types of Websites require constant marketing to drive growth and it can be as expensive as opening a brick and a mortar store.

Amakena makes use of the viral growth that characterizes social network sites and presents retailers and business owners with a great channel to reach their target demographics.

Retailers would simply catalog their products to create a virtual store called an â€œAStoreâ€. Each time a customer chooses to buy items from Amakena, AStores that contain these items are listed for the user to choose from. 

Amakena handles all logistical issues such as payment methods, shipment, etc. and creates a care free environment for the retailers to benefit from.
column40:
With too many options on hand, how do people decide on which new places to try, which books to read, TV series to watch, Music to listen to, etc? We have conducted a survey on 375 people, in the 18 - 44 age group that shows that people usually rely on their friends, people who share the same taste, expert reviews and the public opinion (e.g. Best Sellers, Box Office, etc.) as a big factor of their decision making process.

Amakena is a social cataloging website that provides users with an easy way to organize and share their favourite interests like books, movies, TV series and music among others with their friends, write reviews, share ratings, get recommendations based on their personal preferences, meet others with similar taste, buy their favorite items and get them delivered in the comfort of their homes.

column40:
The Ballerina Energy System that is being developed at SES is to respond to the urgent need to lower greenhouse gas emissions from household users.    
This new product is made of a spherical sun receiver linked with a wind mill.  The Ballerina follows the sun for maximum efficiency.  It also has a dual flexible receiver that switches between a concentrated PV receiver or a hot black plate for water heating.  The windmill is located below the spherical receiver and is independent of the above system. The Ballerina base provides the brain of the system and has all the necessary controls namely: two large liquid reservoirs for hot and or/cold water storage.  A large set of batteries used to store electricity from the wind turbine and from the PV concentrated panel.  The base has also the inverter, and necessary pumps along with a general controller that would be linked to the household user showing him or her in real time how much the system is producing electricity and heat (hot/cold) and the amount of energy produced and stored.  The system can also communicate with other Ballerina"s and share energies (i.e. if one user of a house does not use all his electricity needs and has an excess), he or she can transfer this energy to another Ballerina, hence not only the optimization is on a micro-user but it could be expended to a community of users.  The name "Ballerina" was used to reflect its gracious sun tracking and simultaneous wind rotation with its flexibility to manage energy.
This product is a complete, efficient and smart renewable energy system that works during day and night.  It also combines heat storage and cold storage that could be done during the night using stored electrical energy or from wind.  The Ballerina controller decides when to produce heat/cold or when to produce electricity.  On a windy and cloudy day, the Ballerina may stop tracking the sun and position itself vertically for maximum wind energy production.  It"s built in anemometer and sun energy sensors, along with the existing energy storage system and user history would allow the Ballerina to decide how best to optimize the system for maximum energy supply.  The Ballerina is needed as it fills a need for consumers that are still undecided on what to purchase to cut down their energy needs.  Consumers are struggling whether to buy a Solar Water Heater or a stand alone PV panel system or Wind System.  Now they have the option to buy one system that optimizes all three.  The consumer does not have to worry anymore on what to buy as the Ballerina satisfies all his or her energy needs in a practical and simple way.

column16: This project aims to invent and investigate an environmentally friendly process to remove synthetic dyes and metals from textile wastewater. This is biotechnology in a very fundamental and environmentally friendly application.  It is based on using selected strains of actinomycetes that showed unique abilities in synthetic dyes degradation and heavy metals detoxification.  This method will be much less costly than the current physical and chemical treatment methods.  It will detoxify the heavy metals in the wastewater to harmless forms rather than creating a problematic solid waste that requires additional treatment before disposal. Additionally, and more environmentally important, the compounds that actinomycetes produce to break down the dyes are enzymes and proteins that themselves are easily broken down in nature to basic amino acids.

column40: In recent years, a number of studies have focused on some microorganisms that are able to biodegrade synthetic compounds and biosorb heavy metals in wastewater. Our microbiology research team was able to isolate special types of naturally occurring types of filamentous bacteria - called actinomycetes - from industrial effluent at 10th Ramadan City. The abilities of these strains for degrading a variety of synthetic hydrocarbons (polycyclic hydrocarbons, pentachlorophenol, phthalates, organochlorine pesticides, triphenylmethane dyes and azo dyes) as well as abilities for bioremoval of several heavy metals (cadmium, cobalt, chromium, copper, manganese, iron, nickel, zinc and lead) have been investigated. Selected strains facilitated complete mineralization of organic compounds, thus offered a potential for finding effective bioremediation agents for purifying contaminated environments (El-Shatoury, 2001; El-Shatoury, et al., 2004). Pathway and molecular basis of organochlorines degradation as well as mechanisms of chromium removal by actinomycetes consortium has been worked out (El-Shatoury, et al., 2005; Diab, et al., 2007; Abdulla, et al., 2009; Kamal, 2009).

column16:
The product is innovative because to this day, no one provides turn-key finishing and furnishing in our society. Additionally, there is a specific lack of focus when it comes to low-middle income housing. With the changes that have occurred in the region, we believe a middle class will begin to surface, a class that will be aspiring to obtain modern and classic design concepts and interior finishing at affordable prices.
Additionally, the project provides a material service that is usually time consuming and exhausting, in a manner that conforms with the nature of todayâ€™s young society: fast, affordable and efficient.
column29:
The project will have several positive impacts on society, namely:
1. With any developing economy, people seek more automation and turn-key solutions to be able to devote more time to their jobs, which will become increasingly challenging. Our project allows youth the utilize their time more efficiently by effectively outsourcing the finishing and furnishing process in a reliable timely turn-key manner.

2. The project will enhance the skills and efficiency of local furniture workers, creating more jobs in the industry, and streamlining its performance to meet consumer demand.

3. By offering cheap financing, the project will allow low-middle income youth to contribute more actively to economic growth by stimulating purchases of appliances, construction materials, and other items needed for the finishing process.
column32:
The problems we are addressing are:
1. The inability of today"s young society to be able to finance their residences" finishing and furnishing. The ability to finance furniture does exist in a limited fashion, however, because finishing is usually completed by small, semi-formal companies, financing is usually not an option.

2. The lack of space-saving and efficient furniture that complies with the limited spaces available to today"s low-middle income youth. Floor space is expensive, and furniture in the region has not yet adapted to match the increasingly demanding needs of consumers.

3. The availability of skilled furniture workers that have no access to smart designs, while their skill levels can be commendable.

4. The time-consuming process that is finishing and furnishing a house or an apartment, which is faced by many low-middle income newly-weds, who are usually torn apart between their daily obligations and the errands that come with finishing and furnishing a house. Additionally, the process may be elongated by lack of funds, which is also a major issue faced by many youth, and one that can be easily solved by cheap financing.
column40: The idea behind our project is to provide turn-key finishing and furnishing for low to middle income housing. Utilizing modern concepts and space saving designs, coupled with local mass production, cheap and semi-skilled construction labor, we would be able to provide quality interior finishing at competitive prices.

column40:
[Shared-Meal] vision is to create the largest chain of restaurant alternatives around the world by encouraging cooking enthusiasts (the hosts) to operate their houses as very unique places to serve meals.

The only thing required from the hosts is to plan what they will cook for their families for a week in advance then publish their (meal plans) on [Shared-Meal] to be viewed by meal buyers (the guests). The guest selection of a meal can be based on her/his taste, availability date, the host profile, the place profile, and even shared interests! When the guest confirms a reservation, the host will only extend the planned meal to be enough for his family and for the guest. The guest share of the meal can either be sent to him through a delivery service provider to his location or it can be served in the host place where both (the host and the guest) can meet to have the planned meal and to share a mutual conversation about a topic that interests both of them.

[Shared-Meal] mission is to help cooking enthusiasts start their businesses in the meal industry using their existing resources. Also, [Shared-Meal] is expanding social networks between hosts and guests by simply connecting them to enjoy a delicious shared meal.

column18:
Main Competitors: GoEjaza have 4 types of direct & indirect competitors:

1- Arabic travel forums (example: http://travel.maktoob.com/vb - http://www.sfari.com/forums/ ) :
Pros:
The main competitors in this market, one of richest sources for Arabic travel content created by users.
Cons:
The classical method of showing the data in the forums but obstacles for user to find & obtain the information he needs from other person trip report, user needs to read too many pages with too many unnecessary replies from people who comment, for example you need to read from to 15 to 23 page as an average -for each trip report- to obtain the information you want from one person trip report he shared in the forum !.
however GoEjaza is different ?
GoEjaza platform overcomes these obstacles & make it easy for both ( user who share his trip report & user who want to benefit from this story) to easy share the information about his trip in a new effective way.

2-International review and planning sites like :
(examples: www.igougo.com - www.tripadvisor.com )
Pros:
Organized content & reviews regarding hotels or restaurants or tourism destinations
Cons:
- The content in these websites is in English.
- Majority of users of these websites are not from the region. This obviously appears in lack of Arabic users using these websites & explain large number of visitors & users of Arabic travel forums because it"s the only platform available to Arabic users to share their travel experience.
however Goejaza is different ?
First: we build goejaza.com for people who searches for original travel content by Arabic users having similar culture
Second: also we are not just a website that collect reviews about places like hotels, restaurant"s, ... etc, we go beyond that by offering a tool make you plan your trip online and made bookings for all your trip activities in one place.

3-Booking websites like (http://booking.com, http://www.fendeq.com/):
pros: 
- Provide hotels booking services
- Some websites also provide flight and cars reservations .
Some websites show users review s of hotels from tripadvisor or using simple review system in the hotel information page.
cons:
- no information about travel destination ... show only information about hotels, with minority presence of user reviews.
- No added value for users, except reservation services.
how is GoEjaza different ?
GoEjaza is a complete trip experience start from inspiring user for his next trip to crowdsource information from real traveller experience ending with planning & booking, and these competitors don"t over anything more to the user except the booking & information about hotels.

4-The Tourism Companies :
pros:
Personalized service.
Offers complete Trip packages.
Cons:
-Majority serving the customers through office during time of works. And that need to be visited thought customers.
-Don"t offers Detailed information about hotels like photos and customer reviews.
how is GoEjaza different ?
As the past competitors GoEjaa provide complete Added values services to enrich traveller trip experience. The tourism companies doesn"t provide after sale value or services to the customer.
GoEjaza Help The traveller from the inspiration, bookings of all trip activities and make acceptable from any device. Helping the user by reminding him about his daily plan portable with him from his mobile or tablet or laptop.

column18:
KLoad is having the advantages as the first mover offering location based transportation management services in Egypt. This gives us a strong advantage over competitors. 
Direct competition:
4-	 Trucking brokers: KLoad will have the advantage of access to the location information of a big number of trucks. In addition, shippers will have instant online access to KLoad to communicate their trucking needs.
5-	Trucking contractors: Contractors are specialized in on type of tucking service. They will have more flexibility in serving customers with using their owned trucks. Yet, they donâ€™t offer value added service offered by KLoad (such as document management/reporting). In addition, their service is not reliable because of lack of access to a wide range of truck owners. 
6-	Transportation management solutions providers (TMS). KLoad offered as SAAS (software as a service) is much lower in cost and implementation/training time than TMS. In addition, we offer location information about trucks and shipments. 
7-	Large trucking companies. Own less that 3% of trucks. Most of large trucking companies act as freight forwarders and use their fleet to serve their clients. 
Indirect competitors, Freight forwarders: Most of ports freight trucking is done via Freight forwards who offer clearance and door to door transportation to clients. KLoad short term strategy is to offer its service to class A&B freight forwarders where we can keep competitive rates and sell value added service.
column19:
Linking trucks to available load via KLoad will have a significant impact in the following areas:
1-Reduce final product cost: reducing transportation cost will reflect on final product cost. Cost reduction will make the product more competitive locally and in the international market. 
2- Reduce CO2 emission: Road transport consumes 30% of Egypt subsidized fuel and emits 28 million ton of CO2 per year. Increasing the truck productivity will reduce the amount of emitted CO2 and wasted fuel consumed by empty travelling trucks. 
4-Improve road safety: Trucks cause 40% of road accident in Egypt, a major cause of accidents is poor maintenance specially tires (Flat tires cause 20% of accidents). Increasing the economic productivity of vehicles will help owners (90% of trucks are owned by individuals) to spend on regular truck maintenance

column22:
Heavy trucks travel empty for 70-80% of return trips. The low performance of heavy trucks results in higher transportation cost due to the fuel, oil and tires wasted during the empty travel. 
15% of the trucks is Egyptâ€™s 500,000 truck are heavy trucks. The heavy trucking fleet transport 60% of the estimated 450 million ton of freight in Egypt. 
The transportation cost can be lowered by 30% if information about truck location and available loads are available. 
KLoad innovation comes from offering the following:
1- Location based service: Using Cell ID/GPS tracking to link trucks to available loads.
2- On demand TMS: Providing a low cost and easy to use Transportation Management System for small and medium enterprises. 
3- Mobile access: Providing mobile interface to drivers/truck owners to allow easy communication in addition to the desktop interface.
column32:

 Other major revenue s source will be selling value added service to corporate using a freemium model. Our target in 5 years is to reach 1000 corporate subscriber with gross revenue of 1 million USD.

1-Personal experience: Karim & Hani owns a truck for 6 month. 50% of the time our truck was empty. If the truck had loads on return trips that would have reduced the price of transportation by 30%

*Misr National Transport Study, Jica, March 2012
*Reducing Transport Cost of Egyptâ€™s Exports, USAID, 1999
column40:
KLoad : connecting trucks to loads 
KLoad is a location based transportation management system (TMS) that connects trucks to available loads. Shipper uses an online company account to place their shipment orders. Using location based technology and available trucks details; KLoad will be able to locate trucks nearest to the shipment and directs the driver through mobile communication to the shipment.   
 KLoad will offer other value added service such as document management, shipment tracking, and history reports, and billing information to clients.

column19: Our goal is to solve social issues through business. The social issue at hand is youth unemployment. Our venture will have a positive impact on the community by making it less risky for companies to hire college graduates. By reducing uncertainty, companies will find it more attractive to hire recent graduates with no professional experience. Our venture will contribute to the employment of the youth.
column21: The money will go towards web development  and the development of the psychometric test.
column22:
25% of the youth in the Arab world are unemployed. This gets more problematic given that a third of the population in the Arab World is between 15 - 29 years. Youth unemployment is very costly as it hinders the development of Arab countries. The monetary cost of youth unemployment reaches $40 to $50 billion a year. 

There is a huge gap between college students and the private sector. The private sector faces uncertainty when hiring a recent graduate as there is no background experience that they could rely on to reduce the risk associated with their selection. Moreover, college students seeking full-time positions find it very difficult to market themselves and to legitimize their skills and abilities as a great fit. 

What makes the problem more complicated is the application process. College graduates applying to entry-level positions face difficulties finding the applications online and then filling them out. Entry-level applicants usually do not have rich professional experience that supports their credentials, which leaves an undesirable amount of white space in their applications.  

Companies in the Middle East differ in terms of their speed in adopting online job applications. Many companies have an informal application process, which mainly depends on networks. This limits the pool of candidates a company has. It also confines the applicants to a small number of potential employers, which reduces their chances of getting a job offer.
column29: Our venture is very scalable. The business model works in any developing country with high youth unemployment. Our ability to scale will mainly depend on securing partnerships with companies.
column32: Applicants will be able to access the website and apply for jobs for free. However, applicants will have to pay to take advantage of other services including resume and job consultation. Private and public companies as well as multinationals will be paying annual fees for our services. SMEs will be charged on a monthly basis.
column40: Our idea is to create a website tailored for entry-level applicants. Applicants will be able to search for positions that meet their qualifications and apply online. To reduce uncertainty and the risk associated with hiring college graduates, each applicant will have to complete a psychometric test. The psychometric test assesses applicantsâ€™ business acumen, personality traits, abilities and attitudes. Each applicant will receive a score (similar to a credit score) and companies will have the freedom to decide on which range they are willing to accept. Using psychometrics reduces the risks associated with hiring recent graduates with no professional experience. It also enables companies to identify applicants that fit their companiesâ€™ culture and hence, have a better chance of succeeding at their job. As a result, companies will reduce turnover and spend less on developmental programs.

Other competitors:

Competitive position:
No other business in Egypt focuses exclusively on the quality of the information that can be needed by the SME"s in their business field or integrating them in a one website on the internet. This benefit or this competitive advantage can provide the website a high attention getter to it from different levels of companies or sectors in the Egyptian market.

In addition to that,Wasla.com website will offer a high quality database that integrate different information that are in a need by the SME"S .Then Wasla.com will be expanded in another three countries after the 5 years of operations.

But Wasla.com has an integrated network with a competitive advantage over the other competitors, which as it was mentioned the integration and the focusing in different business sectors that will be needed by the SME"s in their business. All these information will be in a one place with a high quality control.

As AUC witnesses a huge change to the food outlets seen in its new campus, which comes in a 
time when the newly-enrolled students reached 1,200 students this year, ordering food became a 
major issue at AUCâ€™s new campus. Instead of using breaks for extracurricular activities and/or taking a break, as they are was meant to be used, students and faculty find themselves in a race against time to get the food they want and have the time to eat it while doing any other commitments. What seems to be a solution is to avoid ordering food during assembly hours (a break given to the whole AUC community, it is from 1-2 pm everyday) and utilizing the 15-minute breaks between classes, but this never works, because everyone does it. The main reason for this problem is that AUCâ€™s food outlets system was not built to accept such a huge inflow, especially during assembly hours and upon bus arrivals. Not only does this annoy the AUC community, it affects the profits these outlets make as well; we believe that the solution to this is for AUC to have an efficient pre-ordering system. Engezny originated to solve this problem.
column40:
Engezny is a food pre-ordering system that allows both customers to order food from any food outlet without being there physically and to pick it up at 
the time they wish. The pre-ordering system allows its users to log in through a website and to order food and also pay for it.
The purpose of the  Engezny  is to save  the  time and effort wasted on waiting to order in the different outlets due to the long waiting lines. In addition, Engezny aspires to enhance the quality of food ordered through having the outlets aware of the orders beforehand and providing them  with enough time and space to schedule preparing the orders rather than rushing them out due to crowded outlets.

As we are student at the American University in Cairo AUC, we attempt to first implement the project on small scope on campus because we already face a problem in food queues in breaks.

column22:
My Idea will try to solve the problem of the high cost of books. The reader will not be obliged to buy every book that he read and then keep it in his cupboard without any use.
The reader will not be obliged to take transportation and go to public libraries because he will get the book at his house only.
Usually public libraries are having a limit number of books wich is  renewed after a long time (one year almost). But in My shared library there will be a new books avery day coming from the participation of new readers.
column29:
Every day new people will participate in my Library and they will send a book for avery one to get inscription in my Library. With this way my data base of books will increase daily and the number of participants also because a big diversity of books will be there.
In the hole world people are interested by reading books so my project can be spread all over the world
column32:
For Exemple 1 000 000 person will give a book to participate in my Library. Like this i will have 1000 000 book. If monthly 30 % of books are hired so 300 000 book will be exchanged.
For every book exchanged, the reader will pay 2.5 $ Dollar. 2 dollars will be the cost of sending and receiving back the book . 0.5 dollar will be my profit in every exchange.
It means my profit will be monthly : P = 300 000 x  0.5 $ = 150 000 $ Monthly

column19:
MENA region had no such service but it all shares the
same thing "A lot of falsified goods" Medicine, food,
cars spare parts. you name it !! customers are always
suspicious about the goods they buy. One good
example is the electrical accessories market in Egypt
where brands like Siemens and GE suffer from cheap
grey market products which may cause fire in customer
place. Saudia Arabia , UAE, Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco
and Jordan are all suffering the same issues.
Wherever there are falsified goods in the market
"Assly" can make a real difference by offering secure and reliable service that can protect against falsification. 
For the businesses like pharmaceuticals and spare parts manufactures and distributors such service will mean less profit losses and more fund to spend on research and development.
column22:
The falsification of goods; specially medicine and car spare parts is a huge problem in MENA region. Estimates of counterfeited medicine in Egypt only is estimated at 3 Billion EGP per year (source http://www.elshaab.org/thread.php?ID=39962)
Jordan is another country that suffers the same problem with 10 Billion Dinar (Source http://www.alfanonline.com/show_news.aspx?nid=18814&pg=4)
All around the world the market of falsified goods including medicine is estimated between 70 to 120 Billion US$ !!
In Africa there are 700,000 death per year due to falsified medicine.
The number of people who die due to falsified car spare parts is huge as well.
Watching this video can show how severe is this in our region.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wijRo6riWEw

column40: ENCODE studio is a "design by research studio" created by the collaboration of young architects that have come together to break the status quo and go beyond the typical architecture studio by developing the pragmatic use of various digital media in the architecture and the design practice. They are dedicated to explore integrated architecture computational design techniques and innovative design systems on different scales from object to field aiming for a more significant Egyptian presence in the global design market.  ENCODE team believes in research as a catalyst of innovation in the design industry. They intended to be a conduit between design professionals, the educational and the manufacturing sectors by investigating various digital and physical computational tools based on the mathematical and material logic of natural systems, exploring the potentials of digital design and fabrication techniques to correlate education, profession and design industry.

Every body knows We had a huge unemployment problem in Egypt and Mena  area We have an unemployment rate around 12% in Egypt. Even most of the employed young people needs second income source to be able to support their families. 
On the other hand many people are very busy and stressed and they will be very happy if we can find them someone who can finish the simple daily tasks that takes much time and  effort for a reasonable price and  this is why we are building taskty.

Taskty is a simple tasks  assigning platform. Our job will be to connecting those people together ,ensure quality of service, offer a convenient payment method  and make sure that the process is safe.
 
So how does it work?
When need to hire someone for a task you can submit your task with all the details and the required talents that should present in the service provider to finish the job and the price you offer. 
 Freelancers will start to apply for the task until  you choose one of them. we will help you to choose better by our advanced recommendation and rating system. 
once the task is done and you are satisfied we will finalize the task, transferring the money and record the ratings. 
we just published an extensive customer survey to get a list with the services with the highest need but here are some examples: 
If you have a small business we will help you to hire freelancers to finish graphic design (logo flyer , b card etc),copywriting job , simple legal advising or event organization .  
Also you can ask for someone to deliver you something, help you with cooking, photographing an event or even do house cleaning or a simple maintenance.

Cairo- then Egypt then MENA then scaling up globally.
For starting our market and target market are as follows:
Our target market based on the statistics conducted on the entrepreneurial activity in Egypt by the World Bank group and our market research survey are youth holding bachelor or higher university degrees that constitute 27% of entrepreneurial active population of 2.7 million with 35% gaining income of 10,000 LE or more. With 63% of entrepreneurs belief of entrepreneurial potential, but business discontinuation or failure to start due to lack of entrepreneurial knowledge, access to networks and finance; empowerment to develop and sustain their businesses in a community of 27.1% unemployment rate, millions of immigrants seeking job opportunities, brain drainage, splitting families apart and economy decline. PIN IT will provide this target market with their needs, answer their questions, get them altogether enabling them to access network of partner universities, academic and media sponsors and be mentored by key figures in different fields to reflect on their business, access finance and leap to next steps impact communities generating wealth and job opportunities for others being charged 800$ less than a team member half income. This market has huge potential of expansion after growing in Cairo the center of entrepreneurial activity to other needy location, generating jobs, empowering youth to access finance and create new markets, it is a sustainable job and market generator, creating 75 jobs minimum per graduating company.

column22:
Over 90% of creatives in Saudi Arabia believe there is a lack of:
- collaborative workspace where they can work together and learn from each other
- creative communities and networking opportunities where they can find support from like minded people and receive feedback on their work
- affordable workshops where they can develop their skills
- online database that gives creatives in Saudi Arabia more exposure and provides the opportunity to connect with creatives with the same specialty

Furthermore, start ups and social initiatives need the support of creatives and therefore Onqoud"s platform will facilitate the process of finding creatives.

Onqoud aims to collaborate with likeminded ventures and initiatives in order to amplify the positive impact on the community and to enrich the creative scene in Saudi Arabia.

column16: First Saudi Arabia, then the Gulf States. After the softwareâ€™s success, I would start expanding in the MENA. Afterwards I would go globally. The main customers are governmental traffic departments and corporations that offer traffic control solutions.
column18: The main competitors are companies that offer traffic control solutions. On the other hand, the indirect competitors are legislator who might enforce harsh traffic laws in order to reduce traffic accidents. However, the legislatorâ€™s solutions constantly proved to be ineffective my main targeted market (Saudi Arabia).
column19: The business would have a huge positive effect on the community. The reason behind this is that the main target of the business is to achieve a positive externality on the community (reduce traffic accidents) which would have a huge positive impact. Reducing traffic accidents would save lives by reducing related fatalities. It would also reduce injuries, which would also reduce medical costs and insurance.  Moreover, it would reduce the $6 billion that Saudi spends each year on traffic accidents management. Another positive economic effect would be that traffic jams would be reducing, because of the reduction I the number of accidents that caused it. Reducing traffic accidents might also help the environment, because of the reduction in number of vehicles being disposed each year. The business would also create high tech well-paid jobs for employees who will work on developing and operating the software. Saving lives, having positive effects on the economy and the environment makes TARS a win-win business for both the investors and the community.
column21: To develop and produce the software.
column22: The main problem is traffic accidents. Saudi Arabia has a very high rate of traffic accidents. Moreover, most of the solutions implemented to solve this problem proved to be ineffective. According to Saudiâ€™s Secretary-general of Intelligent Transport Systems (ITC), in 2012 the Saudi government spent $6 billion on the management of traffic accidents, while traffic accidents fatalities increased 10% (Source: Jiffry, F., 2012. Experts rate Saudi roads as among the worldâ€™s most dangerous. Arab News, [online] 8 November. Available at: < http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/experts-rate-saudi-roads-among-world%E2%80%99s-most-dangerous> [Accessed 26 January 2013].)
column29: There is a regional demand for cheap innovative solutions for traffic accidents. The business is very scalable because it can satisfy this demand with little changes made to the software. Moreover, these changes and tweaks to the software that will make it suitable for other markets are few (mainly maps and interface language). The few changes indicate that there will be an increase in profits without a proportionate increase in costs.
column32: selling the software, subscriptions to the software, and the after sales services.
column39: The first step was to investigate traffic accidents reduction solutions implemented in Saudi Arabia and the Gulf states. The solutions were assessed by comparing the number of traffic accidents, related number of fatalities/injuries in different years. All these numbers had an increasing trend, while the solutions implemented failed constantly. Moreover, most of the solutions were legislations and laws which produced general unconcentrated efforts to deal with the problem.
column40: TARS collects traffic accidents data, analyse it, and help implementing and evaluating its solutions. TARS will have a smart phone app that traffic officers use to report traffic accidents that they handle (Reporting locations, times, number of injuries, and deaths). The smart phone app will crowd source the data collection process creating a huge mine of data for the software to analyse. The software will produce an interactive map with each cluster of accidents represented as a point. The colour of the each point represents the frequency of accidents (red for high, orange for medium, and yellow for low). When clicking on any accidents point a profile will appear, containing the pointâ€™s details. The details include its number, status, and historical data. The employees must suggest a solution to reduce the accidents in this point, using data that the software analysed. After inserting the solution, the software starts tracking the change in the rate of accidents, deaths, and injuries in the point. Solutions can be viewed and sorted depending on district, status, and rate of change. This feature enables the traffic department to identify the employees or teams with best/worst solutions, which can become a field of competition. The software will be able to learn from the users and starts recognising patters, which enables it to start suggesting solutions for accident points, or even modifications for current implemented solutions.

â€œTouching Careâ€ is the only social network customized for Alzheimerâ€™s society and developed in English and Arabic and soon in other languages. It provides innovative integrated system with a large variety of useful features to support each of the three main users: caregivers, Alzheimerâ€™s patients and physicians. They all encounter different problems related to the onset of the disease.

â€¢	Caregivers: 
Alzheimerâ€™s disease put caregivers on strenuous and tremendous emotional, social, physical and financial stress. Caregivers lack daily social and emotional support, which leads them to fall into depression and feel helpless. Thus â€œTouching Careâ€ provides caregivers with a window to speak through a feature called â€œLoungeâ€, where they can share their stories and experiences, voice their concerns and seek knowledge and needed support. 
Caregivers undergo tremendous stress and pressure due to the lack of a system or tool that help them organize their day to day activities, develop better coping strategies, reduce their burden and empower them with the knowledge on best practices in dealing with this disease. â€œTouching Careâ€ addresses those needs through â€œCalendar and Medication Plannerâ€ where caregivers can organize in a user-friendly way the entire medical condition of the patient and track daily changes. Caregivers can generate a daily checklist to track the overall health of the patient, which make the life of caregivers easier as it reduce their care giving burden. Many caregivers find it difficult to find the care products needed to provide a good care for the Alzheimerâ€™s patient. â€œTouching Careâ€ solve this pressing issue through â€œAids and Toolsâ€ feature, which aim to provide caregivers with the tools and equipments needed to look after their loved ones.
â€¢	Alzheimerâ€™s patients:
Alzheimer patients suffers because of the lack of Alzheimerâ€™s friendly community specially that unfortunately the community tend usually to stigmatize the person with Alzheimerâ€™s and perceive him/her as someone unconscious, useless, and cannot be engaged in the social activities. This isolation and neglecting consequently increases Alzheimerâ€™s patientâ€™s levels of depression and anxiety, which is proved scientifically to accelerate the onset of their deterioration. Furthermore, Alzheimerâ€™s patients lack the tools that help them to stimulate their memory and cognition. Studies have shown that the patient requires intensive mental stimulation to slow the onset of the disease and level of deterioration. â€œTouching Careâ€ therefore provides â€œReminiscenceâ€ or mental stimulation tools through â€œPhoto Albumâ€ feature, â€œMultimedia Studioâ€ feature, â€œMemory Games â€œ and â€œDiariesâ€ features. 
â€¢	Physicians:
Physicians lack a system that helps them track their patientâ€™s medical condition, capture real-time/dynamic information necessarily to track the patientâ€™s progress and provide accurate diagnosis. â€œTouching Careâ€ therefore empower physicians with the ability to track patient daily medical condition and generate user-friendly graphs for better clarity and visibility.
 Thus, to address the needs of the entire ecosystem: caregivers, Alzheimerâ€™s patients, and physicians. â€œTouching Careâ€ comes to pick up on all these dimensions with its integrated, interactive, enriching features and appealing user experience.

â€œTouching Careâ€ is a mobile application for the Alzheimerâ€™s community of caregivers and early stage patients. It is developed for Apple devices and stands as the only specialized social network and comprehensive integrated management tool for people affected by Alzheimerâ€™s. The application is available in both English and Arabic (French and Spanish languages are currently under development) and serves as a platform where both caregivers and patients can organize their day-to-day activities socialize and communicate with their peers and friends as well as other groups that share similar interests. 
In Saudi Arabia alone there are more than one million people suffering from Alzheimerâ€™s disease with numerous others throughout the Arab world. â€œTouching Careâ€ is the only application available in Arabic.
â€œTouching Careâ€ is inspired by its motto, which is "One more way to show them that you care!" and believes that "Alzheimerâ€™s is a battle you can fight, we can help!"
The first stage of Touching Care is a prototype targeted for Alzheimerâ€™s so that we can target its usage in a known community but future versions aim to expand for elderly usage as well as any community in which a caregiver would benefit from an integrated system.
